Class StringReader

Provides rich methods to extract information from a string instance.

Item[Int32]

Gets the System.Char of the underlying string instance using an index relative to the reader's current position. For example, 0 indicates the character at the reader's current position, 1 indicates the character next to the reader's current position, and -1 indicates the character previous to the reader's current position.

Declaration

Count(Char, Boolean)

Counts the number of occurrences of the specified keyChr character that appears at the beginning of the current reading scope until the first keyChr character is encountered (first non-white-space non-keyChr character if ignoreWhiteSpaces is set true). The reader will advance the position to the non-keyChr character that stops the counting.

Declaration
public int Count(char keyChr, bool ignoreWhiteSpaces = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Char keyChr

The target character.
System.Boolean ignoreWhiteSpaces

If set to true, the white spaces at the beginning of the reader's current reading scope will be ignored.
Returns
Type Description
System.Int32

The number of occurrences of the specified keyChr character that appears at the beginning of the current reading scope.
| Improve this Doc View Source

GetKeyValuePairEnumerator(Char, Char, Char, Char, Boolean)

Gets an enumerator that iterates through key/value pairs represented by this StringReader if its reading scope follows certain syntax.

Declaration
public IEnumerator<KeyValuePair<string, string>> GetKeyValuePairEnumerator(char keyDelimiter = '=', char pairDelimiter = ';', char leftQuote = '[', char rightQuote = ']', bool trimValue = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Char keyDelimiter

The Unicode character that delimits key and value in each pair. In each pair, only the first character that equals this argument will be recognized as a delimiter, and it cannot be escaped.
System.Char pairDelimiter

The Unicode character that delimits key/value pairs. This delimiter is escapable.
System.Char leftQuote

The Unicode character as the left escaping quote for pairDelimiter. Use '\0' to indicate the escape is disabled.
System.Char rightQuote

The Unicode character as the right escape quote for pairDelimiter.
System.Boolean trimValue

true if the white spaces at both ends of the value of each returned pair is trimmed; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerator<System.Collections.Generic.KeyValuePair<System.String, System.String>>

An enumerator that iterates through key/value pairs represented by this StringReader.
Remarks

To parse the current reading scope as key/value pairs, the reading scope must follow the syntax (<key> <key/value delimiter> [<left escaping quote>]<value> <pair delimiter>[<right escaping quote>]) (...n).

If the pairDelimiter is ';' (default value) and the escape is disabled, this string must follow the syntax (<key> = <value>;) (...n), which is exactly the same as a standard database connection string.

| Improve this Doc View Source

Type Description
System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerator<System.Collections.Generic.KeyValuePair<System.String, StringReader>>

An enumerator that iterates through key/value pairs represented by this StringReader. In each returned pair, the value is represented by a StringReader.
Remarks

To parse the current reading scope as key/value pairs, the reading scope must follow the syntax (<key> <key/value delimiter> [<left escaping quote>]<value> <pair delimiter>[<right escaping quote>]) (...n).

If the pairDelimiter is ';' (default value) and the escape is disabled, this string must follow the syntax (<key> = <value>;) (...n), which is exactly the same as a standard database connection string.

GetSplitEnumerator(Char, Boolean, Boolean)

Gets an object that can iterate through substrings of the current reading scope that are delimited by the specified Unicode character as the separator.

Declaration
public IEnumerator<string> GetSplitEnumerator(char separator, bool removeEmptyEntries = true, bool trim = false)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Char separator

A Unicode character as the separator.
System.Boolean removeEmptyEntries

true if empty strings should not be returned; otherwise false.
System.Boolean trim

Indicates whether the returned substrings are trimmed.

NOTE that if removeEmptyEntries is set true, then a substring containing only white spaces will not be returned; for example, in this case "ab, ,cd" split by comma ',' is "ab" and "cd".
Returns
Type Description
System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerator<System.String>

An object that can iterate through substrings of the current reading scope that are delimited by the specified separator.
| Improve this Doc View Source

GetSplitEnumeratorWithQuotes(Char, Char[], Char[], Boolean, Boolean)

Gets an object that can iterate through substrings of the current reading scope that are delimited by Unicode characters outside quotes and satisfying the specified predicate.

Declaration
public IEnumerator<string> GetSplitEnumeratorWithQuotes(char separator, char[] leftQuotes, char[] rightQuotes, bool removeEmptyEntries = true, bool trim = false)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Char separator

A Unicode character as the separator.
System.Char[] leftQuotes

An array of Unicode characters as the left quotes. A left quote of an index of this array corresponds to the right quote of that index of the array specified by rightQuotes. The reader will not stop when a character satisfying the predicate is encountered inside a pair of quotes.
System.Char[] rightQuotes

An array of Unicode characters as the right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by leftQuotes. The reader will not stop when a character satisfying the predicate is encountered inside a pair of quotes.
System.Boolean removeEmptyEntries

true if empty strings should be removed from the returned substrings; otherwise false.
System.Boolean trim

Indicates whether the returned substrings are trimmed.

NOTE that if removeEmptyEntries is set true, then a substring containing only white spaces will not be returned; for example, in this case "ab, ,cd" split by comma ',' is "ab" and "cd".
Returns
Type Description
System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerator<System.String>

An object that can iterate through substrings in the current string instance (or a part of the current string instance) that are delimited by Unicode characters outside quotes.
Exceptions
Type Condition
System.FormatException

Occurs when there is a quote mismatch in the string instance.

Gets an object that can iterate through substrings (represented by StringReader objects) of the current reading scope that are delimited by the specified Unicode character as the separator.

Declaration
public IEnumerator<StringReader> GetSplitReaderEnumerator(char separator, bool removeEmptyEntries = true, bool trim = false)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Char separator

A Unicode character as the separator.
System.Boolean removeEmptyEntries

true if empty strings should not be returned; otherwise false.
System.Boolean trim

Indicates whether the returned substrings are trimmed.

NOTE that if removeEmptyEntries is set true, then a substring containing only white spaces will not be returned; for example, in this case "ab, ,cd" split by comma ',' is "ab" and "cd".
Returns
Type Description
System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerator<StringReader>

An object that can iterate through substrings (represented by StringReader objects) of the current reading scope that are delimited by the specified separator.

GetSplitReaderEnumeratorWithQuotes(Char, Char[], Char[], Boolean, Boolean)

Gets an object that can iterate through substrings (represented by StringReader objects) of the current reading scope that are delimited by Unicode characters outside quotes and satisfying the specified predicate.

Declaration
public IEnumerator<StringReader> GetSplitReaderEnumeratorWithQuotes(char separator, char[] leftQuotes, char[] rightQuotes, bool removeEmptyEntries = true, bool trim = false)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Char separator

A Unicode character as the separator.
System.Char[] leftQuotes

An array of Unicode characters as the left quotes. A left quote of an index of this array corresponds to the right quote of that index of the array specified by rightQuotes. The reader will not stop when a character satisfying the predicate is encountered inside a pair of quotes.
System.Char[] rightQuotes

An array of Unicode characters as the right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by leftQuotes. The reader will not stop when a character satisfying the predicate is encountered inside a pair of quotes.
System.Boolean removeEmptyEntries

true if empty strings should be removed from the returned substrings; otherwise false.
System.Boolean trim

Indicates whether the returned substrings are trimmed.

NOTE that if removeEmptyEntries is set true, then a substring containing only white spaces will not be returned; for example, in this case "ab, ,cd" split by comma ',' is "ab" and "cd".
Returns
Type Description
System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerator<StringReader>

An object that can iterate through substrings (represented by StringReader objects) in the current string instance (or a part of the current string instance) that are delimited by Unicode characters outside quotes.
Exceptions
Type Condition
System.FormatException

Occurs when there is a quote mismatch in the string instance.

Read()

Declaration
public char Read()
Returns
Type Description

Read(Char, Boolean)

Determines whether the keyChr character equals the first character (first non-whitespace character if ignoreWhiteSpaces is set true) of the reader's reading scope without considering ComparisonType. If so, the reader advances to the next character; otherwise, the reader remains where it was if ignoreWhiteSpaces is set false, or the reader stops at the first non-whitespace character if ignoreWhiteSpaces is set true.

Declaration

System.Boolean ignoreWhiteSpaces

If set to true, the white spaces at the beginning of the reader's current reading scope will be ignored.
Returns

ReadAfter(Char, Boolean, Boolean)

Advances the reader and reads until a character specified by keychar is encountered. The reader stops at the position next to the encountered keychar.

Declaration
public string ReadAfter(char keychar, bool discardKeychar = true, bool readToEndIfKeycharNotFound = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Char keychar

The reader stops when this character is encountered.
System.Boolean discardKeychar

true if the encountered keychar will be discarded and not be included in the returned substring; otherwise, false.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if the keychar is not found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
System.String

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is true, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of the keychar within the search scope when such character is found, or a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the end of the search scope if such character is not found.

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is false, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of the keychar within the search scope when such character is found, or null if such character is not found.

NOTE that whether the keychar is included in the returned substring depends on discardKeychar, and System.String.Empty will be returned if the length of the substring is 0.
| Improve this Doc View Source

Type Description

System.Int32 hitIndex
System.Boolean discardKeychar

true if the encountered keychar will be discarded and not be included in the returned substring; otherwise, false.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if the keychars is not found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
System.String

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is true, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of any of the keychars within the search scope when such character is found outside quotes, or a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the end of the search scope if such character is not found outside quotes.

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is false, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of any of the keychars within the search scope when such character is found outside quotes, or null if such character is not found outside quotes.

NOTE that whether the encountered keychar is inclueded in the returned substring depends on discardKeychar, and System.String.Empty will be returned if the length of the substring is 0.

ReadAfterAsReader(Func<Char, Boolean>, Boolean, Boolean)

Advances the reader and reads until a character satisfying predicate (key char) is encountered. The current reader stops at the position immediately after the position of the key char.

Declaration
public StringReader ReadAfterAsReader(Func<char, bool> predicate, bool discardKeychar = true, bool readToEndIfKeycharNotFound = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Func<System.Char, System.Boolean> predicate

A method to test each character of the reading scope and determines whether it is a key char.
System.Boolean discardKeychar

true if the key char will be discarded and not be included in the returned substring; otherwise, false.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if no character satisfying the predicate is found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
StringReader

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is true, then a new reader will be returned encapsulating either a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found, or a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the end of the search scope if such character is not found.

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is false, then a new reader will be returned encapsulating a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found. When such character cannot be found, a null reference will be returned.

NOTE that whether the character is included in the returned new reader depends on discardKeychar, and EmptyReader will be returned if the length of the substring is 0.
| Improve this Doc View Source

ReadAfterAsReader(Func<Char, Boolean>, Char, Char, Char[], Char[], Boolean, Boolean)

Advances the reader and reads until a character satisfying the specified predicate (key char) is encountered outside quotes. The current reader stops at the position immediately after the position of the key char.

Declaration
public StringReader ReadAfterAsReader(Func<char, bool> predicate, char primaryLeftQuote, char primaryRightQuote, char[] secondaryLeftQuotes, char[] secondaryRightQuotes, bool discardKeychar = true, bool readToEndIfKeycharNotFound = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Func<System.Char, System.Boolean> predicate

A method to test each character of the reading scope and determines whether it is a key char. The reader will not stop when a key char is encountered inside a pair of primary/secondary quotes.
System.Char primaryLeftQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the primary left quote.
System.Char primaryRightQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the primary right quote.
System.Char[] secondaryLeftQuotes

Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the secondary left quotes. A left quote of an index of this array corresponds to the right quote of that index of the array specified by secondaryRightQuotes. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
System.Char[] secondaryRightQuotes

Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the secondary right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by secondaryLeftQuotes. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
System.Boolean discardKeychar

true if the key char will be discarded and not be included in the returned substring; otherwise, false.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if the key char is not found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
StringReader

A new string reader that encapsulates a substring read from the underlying string instance of the current reader.
| Improve this Doc View Source

ReadAfterAsReader(Func<Char, Boolean>, Char[], Char[], Boolean, Boolean)

Advances the reader and reads until a character satisfying predicate (key char) is encountered outside quotes. The current reader stops at the position immediately after the position of the key char.

Declaration
public StringReader ReadAfterAsReader(Func<char, bool> predicate, char[] leftQuotes, char[] rightQuotes, bool discardKeychar = true, bool readToEndIfKeycharNotFound = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Func<System.Char, System.Boolean> predicate

A method to test each character of the reading scope and determines whether it is a key char.
System.Char[] leftQuotes

An array of Unicode characters as the left quotes. A left quote of an index of this array corresponds to the right quote of that index of the array specified by rightQuotes. The reader will not stop when a key char is encountered inside a pair of quotes.
System.Char[] rightQuotes

An array of Unicode characters as the right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by leftQuotes. The reader will not stop when a key char is encountered inside a pair of quotes.
System.Boolean discardKeychar

true if the key char will be discarded and not be included in the returned substring; otherwise, false.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if no character satisfying the predicate is found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
StringReader

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is true, then a new reader will be returned encapsulating either a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found, or a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the end of the search scope if such character is not found.

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is false, then a new reader will be returned encapsulating a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found. When such character cannot be found, a null reference will be returned.

NOTE that whether the character is included in the returned new reader depends on discardKeychar, and EmptyReader will be returned if the length of the substring is 0.
| Improve this Doc View Source

System.Char secondaryLeftQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the secondary left quote. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
System.Char secondaryRightQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the secondary right quote. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
System.Int32 hitIndex

Returns the index of the encountered keyword in the keywords.
System.Boolean discardKeyword

true if the keyword will be discarded and not be included in the returned substring; otherwise, false.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeywordNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if none of the keywords is found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
StringReader

A new string reader that encapsulates a substring read from the underlying string instance of the current reader.
| Improve this Doc View Source

ReadAfterWithTrim(Char, Boolean, Boolean)

Advances the reader and reads until a character specified by keychar is encountered. The reader stops at the position next to the keychar and the white-spaces at both ends of the returned substring will be trimmed.

Declaration
public string ReadAfterWithTrim(char keychar, bool discardKeychar = true, bool readToEndIfKeycharNotFound = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Char keychar

The reader stops when this character is encountered.
System.Boolean discardKeychar

true if the keychar should be discarded and not be included in the returned substring; otherwise, false.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if the keychar is not found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
System.String

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is true, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of the keychar within the search scope when such character is found, or a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the end of the search scope if such character is not found.

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is false, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of the keychar within the search scope when such character is found, or null if such character is not found.

NOTE that whether the keychar is included in the returned substring depends on discardKeychar, and the white spaces at both ends of the substring will be trimmed. Also NOTE System.String.Empty will be returned if the length of the substring after trim is 0.
| Improve this Doc View Source

public string ReadAfterWithTrim(char[] keychars, char primaryLeftQuote, char primaryRightQuote, char[] secondaryLeftQuotes, char[] secondaryRightQuotes, bool discardKeychar = true, bool readToEndIfKeycharNotFound = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Char[] keychars

The reader stops when any character in this array is encountered outside quotes. The reader will not stop when an element of the keychars is encountered inside a pair of primary/secondary quotes.
System.Char primaryLeftQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the primary left quote.
System.Char primaryRightQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the primary right quote.
System.Char[] secondaryLeftQuotes

Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the secondary left quotes. A left quote of an index of this array corresponds to the right quote of that index of the array specified by secondaryRightQuotes. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
System.Char[] secondaryRightQuotes

Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the secondary right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by secondaryLeftQuotes. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
System.Boolean discardKeychar

true if the encountered keychar will be discarded and not be included in the returned substring; otherwise, false.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if the keychars is not found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
System.String

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is true, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of any of the keychars within the search scope when such character is found outside quotes, or a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the end of the search scope if such character is not found outside quotes.

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is false, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of any of the keychars within the search scope when such character is found outside quotes, or null if such character is not found outside quotes.

NOTE that whether the encountered keychar is inclueded in the returned substring depends on discardKeychar, and the white spaces at both ends of the substring will be trimmed. Also NOTE System.String.Empty will be returned if the length of the substring after trim is 0.
| Improve this Doc View Source

Declaration
public string ReadAfterWithTrim(Func<char, bool> predicate, bool discardKeychar = true, bool readToEndIfKeycharNotFound = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Func<System.Char, System.Boolean> predicate

A method to test each character.
System.Boolean discardKeychar

If set to true, the key char will be discarded and not be included in the returned substring.

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if no character satisfying the predicate is found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description

Type Description

ReadAfterWithTrim(Func<Char, Boolean>, Char, Char, Char, Char, Boolean, Boolean)

Advances the reader and reads until a character satisfying the specified predicate (called key char) is encountered outside quotes. The current reader stops at the position immediately after the last character of the encountered keyword and the white-spaces at both ends of the returned new reader will be trimmed.

Declaration

Type Description
System.String

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is false, then a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found, or null if such character is not found.

NOTE that the white spaces at both ends of the substring will be trimmed. Also System.String.Empty will be returned if the length of the substring after trim is 0.

Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the secondary right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by secondaryLeftQuotes. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
System.Boolean discardKeychar

If set to true, the predicate will be discarded and not be included in the returned substring.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if the predicate is not found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
System.String

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is true, then a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found (whether the character is included in the returned substring depends on discardKeychar), or a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the end of the search scope if such character is not found.

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is false, then a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found, or null if such character is not found.

NOTE that the white spaces at both ends of the substring will be trimmed. Also System.String.Empty will be returned if the length of the substring after trim is 0.
| Improve this Doc View Source

Advances the reader and reads until a character specified by keychars is encountered outside quotes. The current reader stops at the position immediately after the last character of the encountered keyword and the white-spaces at both ends of the returned new reader will be trimmed.

Declaration
public StringReader ReadAfterWithTrimAsReader(char[] keychars, char primaryLeftQuote, char primaryRightQuote, char[] secondaryLeftQuotes, char[] secondaryRightQuotes, bool discardKeychar = true, bool readToEndIfKeycharNotFound = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Char[] keychars

The reader stops when any character in this array is encountered outside quotes. The reader will not stop when an element of the keychars is encountered inside a pair of primary/secondary quotes.
System.Char primaryLeftQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the primary left quote.
System.Char primaryRightQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the primary right quote.
System.Char[] secondaryLeftQuotes

Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the secondary left quotes. A left quote of an index of this array corresponds to the right quote of that index of the array specified by secondaryRightQuotes. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
System.Char[] secondaryRightQuotes

Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the secondary right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by secondaryLeftQuotes. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
System.Boolean discardKeychar

true if the encountered keychar will be discarded and not be included in the returned substring; otherwise, false.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if the keychars is not found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
StringReader

A new string reader that encapsulates a substring read from the underlying string instance of the current reader.
| Improve this Doc View Source

ReadAfterWithTrimAsReader(Func<Char, Boolean>, Boolean, Boolean)

Advances the reader and reads until a character satisfying predicate (key char) is encountered. The current reader stops at the position immediately after the encountered key char and the white-spaces at both ends of the returned new reader will be trimmed.

Declaration
public StringReader ReadAfterWithTrimAsReader(Func<char, bool> predicate, bool discardKeychar = true, bool readToEndIfKeycharNotFound = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Func<System.Char, System.Boolean> predicate

A method to test each character of the reading scope and determines whether it is a key char.
System.Boolean discardKeychar

true if the key char will be discarded and not be included in the returned substring; otherwise, false.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound
Returns
Type Description
StringReader

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is true, then a new reader will be returned encapsulating either a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found, or a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the end of the search scope if such character is not found.

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is false, then a new reader will be returned encapsulating a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found. When such character cannot be found, a null reference will be returned.

NOTE that whether the character is included in the returned new reader depends on discardKeychar, and the white spaces at both ends of the substring will be trimmed. Also NOTE EmptyReader will be returned if the length of the substring after trim is 0.
| Improve this Doc View Source

ReadBefore(Char, Boolean)

Advances the reader and reads until a character specified by keychar is encountered. The reader stops at the position of the encountered keychar.

Declaration
public string ReadBefore(char keychar, bool readToEndIfKeycharNotFound = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Char keychar

The reader stops when this character is encountered.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if the keychar is not found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
System.String

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is true, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of the keychar within the search scope when such character is found, or a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the end of the search scope if such character is not found.

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is false, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of the keychar within the search scope when such character is found, or null if such character is not found.

NOTE that System.String.Empty will be returned if the length of the substring is 0.

true if the encountered keychar will be discarded and not be included in the returned substring; otherwise, false.

NOTE that System.String.Empty will be returned if the length of the substring is 0.
| Improve this Doc View Source

Declaration
public string ReadBefore(char[] keychars, char[] primaryLeftQuotes, char[] primaryRightQuotes, char secondaryLeftQuote, char secondaryRightQuote, out int hitIndex, bool readToEndIfKeycharNotFound = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Char[] keychars

The reader stops when any character in this array is encountered outside quotes. The reader will not stop when an element of the keychars is encountered inside a pair of primary/secondary quotes.
System.Char[] primaryLeftQuotes

Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the primary left quotes. A left quote of an index of this array corresponds to the right quote of that index of the array specified by primaryRightQuotes.
System.Char[] primaryRightQuotes

Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the primary right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by primaryLeftQuotes.
System.Char secondaryLeftQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the secondary left quote. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
System.Char secondaryRightQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the secondary right quote. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
System.Int32 hitIndex

Returns the index of the encountered keychar in the keychars.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if the keychars is not found; otherwise, false.

Type Description
System.String

ReadBeforeAsReader(Func<Char, Boolean>, Boolean)

Advances the reader and reads until a character satisfying predicate is encountered. The current reader stops at the position of the key char.

Declaration
public StringReader ReadBeforeAsReader(Func<char, bool> predicate, bool readToEndIfKeycharNotFound = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Func<System.Char, System.Boolean> predicate

A method to test each character of the reading scope and determines whether it is a key char.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if no character satisfying the predicate is found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
StringReader

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is true, then a new reader will be returned encapsulating either a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found, or a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the end of the search scope if such character is not found.

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is false, then a new reader will be returned encapsulating a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found. When such character cannot be found, a null reference will be returned.

NOTE that EmptyReader will be returned if the length of the substring is 0.
| Improve this Doc View Source

Advances the reader and reads until a character satisfying the specified predicate (key char) is encountered outside quotes. The current reader stops at the position of the key char.

Declaration
public StringReader ReadBeforeAsReader(Func<char, bool> predicate, char primaryLeftQuote, char primaryRightQuote, char[] secondaryLeftQuotes, char[] secondaryRightQuotes, bool readToEndIfKeycharNotFound = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Func<System.Char, System.Boolean> predicate

A method to test each character of the reading scope and determines whether it is a key char. The reader will not stop when a key char is encountered inside a pair of primary/secondary quotes.
System.Char primaryLeftQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the primary left quote.
System.Char primaryRightQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the primary right quote.
System.Char[] secondaryLeftQuotes

Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the secondary left quotes. A left quote of an index of this array corresponds to the right quote of that index of the array specified by secondaryRightQuotes. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
System.Char[] secondaryRightQuotes

Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the secondary right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by secondaryLeftQuotes. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if the key char is not found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
StringReader

A new string reader that encapsulates a substring read from the underlying string instance of the current reader.
| Improve this Doc View Source

ReadBeforeAsReader(Func<Char, Boolean>, Char[], Char[], Boolean)

Advances the reader and reads until a character satisfying predicate (key char) is encountered outside quotes. The current reader stops at the position of the key char.

Declaration
public StringReader ReadBeforeAsReader(Func<char, bool> predicate, char[] leftQuotes, char[] rightQuotes, bool readToEndIfKeycharNotFound = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Func<System.Char, System.Boolean> predicate

A method to test each character of the reading scope and determines whether it is a key char.
System.Char[] leftQuotes

An array of Unicode characters as the left quotes. A left quote of an index of this array corresponds to the right quote of that index of the array specified by rightQuotes. The reader will not stop when a key char is encountered inside a pair of quotes.
System.Char[] rightQuotes

An array of Unicode characters as the right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by leftQuotes. The reader will not stop when a key char is encountered inside a pair of quotes.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if no character satisfying the predicate is found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
StringReader

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is true, then a new reader will be returned encapsulating either a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found, or a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the end of the search scope if such character is not found.

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is false, then a new reader will be returned encapsulating a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found. When such character cannot be found, a null reference will be returned.

NOTE that EmptyReader will be returned if the length of the substring is 0.
| Improve this Doc View Source

Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the secondary right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by secondaryLeftQuotes. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
System.Int32 hitIndex

Returns the index of the encountered keyword in the keywords.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeywordNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if none of the keywords is found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
StringReader

A new string reader that encapsulates a substring read from the underlying string instance of the current reader.

ReadBeforeWithTrim(Char, Boolean)

Advances the reader and reads until a character specified by keychar is encountered. The reader stops at the position of the encountered keychar and the white-spaces at both ends of the returned substring will be trimmed.

Declaration
public string ReadBeforeWithTrim(char keychar, bool readToEndIfKeycharNotFound = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Char keychar

The reader stops when this character is encountered.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if the keychar is not found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
System.String

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is true, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of the keychar within the search scope when such character is found, or a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the end of the search scope if such character is not found.

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is false, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of the keychar within the search scope when such character is found, or null if such character is not found.

NOTE that the white spaces at both ends of the substring will be trimmed. Also System.String.Empty will be returned if the length of the substring after trim is 0.
| Improve this Doc View Source

System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if none of the keychars is not found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
System.String

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is true, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of any of the keychars within the search scope when such character is found outside quotes, or a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the end of the search scope if such character is not found outside quotes.

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is false, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of any of the keychars within the search scope when such character is found outside quotes, or null if such character is not found outside quotes.

NOTE that the white spaces at both ends of the substring will be trimmed. Also System.String.Empty will be returned if the length of the substring after trim is 0.
| Improve this Doc View Source

ReadBeforeWithTrim(Func<Char, Boolean>, Char, Char, Char, Char, Boolean)

Advances the reader and reads until a character satisfying the specified predicate (called key char) is encountered outside quotes. The current reader stops at the position of the key char and the white-spaces at both ends of the returned substring will be trimmed.

Declaration
public string ReadBeforeWithTrim(Func<char, bool> predicate, char primaryLeftQuote, char primaryRightQuote, char secondaryLeftQuote, char secondaryRightQuote, bool readToEndIfKeycharNotFound = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Func<System.Char, System.Boolean> predicate

A method to test each character of the reading scope and determines whether it is a key char. The reader will not stop when a key char is encountered inside a pair of primary/secondary quotes.
System.Char primaryLeftQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the primary left quote.
System.Char primaryRightQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the primary right quote.
System.Char secondaryLeftQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the secondary left quote. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.

Returns
Type Description
System.String

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is true, then a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found (whether the character is included in the returned substring depends on discardKeychar), or a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the end of the search scope if such character is not found.

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is false, then a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found, or null if such character is not found.

An array of Unicode characters as the right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by leftQuotes. The reader will not stop when any of the keychars is encountered inside a pair of quotes.
System.Int32 hitIndex

Returns the index of the encountered keychar in the keychars.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if none of the keychars is found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
StringReader

A new string reader that encapsulates a substring read from the underlying string instance of the current reader.
| Improve this Doc View Source

ReadBeforeWithTrimAsReader(Func<Char, Boolean>, Boolean)

Advances the reader and reads until a character satisfying predicate is encountered. The current reader stops at the position of the key char and the white-spaces at both ends of the returned new reader will be trimmed.

Declaration
public StringReader ReadBeforeWithTrimAsReader(Func<char, bool> predicate, bool readToEndIfKeycharNotFound = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Func<System.Char, System.Boolean> predicate

A method to test each character of the reading scope and determines whether it is a key char.
System.Boolean readToEndIfKeycharNotFound

true if the reader should read to the end of the reading scope if no character satisfying the predicate is found; otherwise, false.
Returns
Type Description
StringReader

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is true, then a new reader will be returned encapsulating either a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found, or a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the end of the search scope if such character is not found.

If readToEndIfKeycharNotFound is false, then a new reader will be returned encapsulating a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found. When such character cannot be found, a null reference will be returned.

NOTE that the white spaces at both ends of the substring will be trimmed. Also EmptyReader will be returned if the length of the substring after trim is 0.
| Improve this Doc View Source

public bool ReadStringFollowedByNonLetterOrDigit(string keyWord, bool ignoreWhiteSpaces = true)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.String keyWord

The target substring.
System.Boolean ignoreWhiteSpaces

If set to true, the white spaces at the beginning of the reader's current reading scope will be ignored.
Returns
Type Description
System.Boolean

true if the reader's current reading scope starts with keyWord followed by a non-letter non-digit character, false otherwise.
| Improve this Doc View Source

ReadStringFollowedByWhiteSpace(String, Boolean)

If the reader's current reading scope starts with keyWord followed by either EOF or a whitespace character (defined by System.Char.IsLetterOrDigit(System.Char)), then reads keyWord from the beginning of the current reading scope and advances the reader to the character after the whitespace character.

ReadTo(Char, Boolean, StringReader.ReadOptions)

Advances the reader and reads until a character specified by keychar is encountered. The CurrentPosition after executing this method depends on the options.

Declaration
public string ReadTo(char keychar, bool doubleKeycharEscape, StringReader.ReadOptions options = StringReader.ReadOptions.StopAfterKey | StringReader.ReadOptions.DiscardKey)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Char keychar

The reader stops when this character is encountered.
System.Boolean doubleKeycharEscape

if set to true, an occurrence of double keychar will be an escape of the keychar. For example, if the keychar is single quote ', then the double ' in 'ab''cd' is an escape of ' if this parameter is set true.
StringReader.ReadOptions options

Specifies the reading options.
Returns
Type Description
System.String

If ReadToEnd is specified in options, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of keychar within the search scope when the keychar is found, or a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the end of the search scope if such character is not found. If ReadToEnd is not specified, then null is returned if keychar is not found.

If StopAfterKey is specified, then the reader stops at the position after the encountered keychar; otherwise the reader stops at the position of the encountered keychar.

The keychar is not included in the returned substring if DiscardKey is specified.

The white spaces at the beginning of the substring will be trimmed if TrimStart is specified, and the white spaces at the end of the substring will be trimmed if TrimEnd is specified. System.String.Empty will be returned if the length of the substring after trim is 0.
| Improve this Doc View Source

ReadTo(Char, Char, Char, Char, Char, StringReader.ReadOptions)

Advances the reader and reads until a character specified by keychar is encountered outside quotes. The reader's position after executing this method depends on the options.

Declaration
public string ReadTo(char keychar, char primaryLeftQuote, char primaryRightQuote, char secondaryLeftQuote, char secondaryRightQuote, StringReader.ReadOptions options = StringReader.ReadOptions.StopAfterKey | StringReader.ReadOptions.DiscardKey | StringReader.ReadOptions.ReadToEnd)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Char keychar

The reader stops when this character is encountered outside quotes. The reader will not stop when an keychar is encountered inside a pair of primary/secondary quotes.
System.Char primaryLeftQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the primary left quote.
System.Char primaryRightQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the primary right quote.
System.Char secondaryLeftQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the secondary left quote. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
System.Char secondaryRightQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the secondary right quote. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
StringReader.ReadOptions options

Specifies the reading options.
Returns
Type Description
System.String

If ReadeOptions.ReadToEnd is specified in options, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of the keychar within the search scope when such character is found outside quotes, or a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the end of the search scope if such character is not found outside quotes.

If ReadeOptions.ReadToEnd is not specified, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of the keychar within the search scope when such character is found outside quotes, or null if such character is not found outside quotes.

The position of this reader after executing this method depends on if ReadOptions.StopAfterKey is specified. If ReadOptions.StopAfterKey is specified, then the character satisfying the predicate is included in the returned substring if ReadOptions.DiscardKey is also selected.

NOTE that the white spaces at the beginning of the substring will be trimmed if ReadeOptions.TrimStart is specified, and the white spaces at the end of the substring will be trimmed if ReadeOptions.TrimEnd is specified. Also NOTE that System.String.Empty will be returned if the length of the substring after trim is 0.

ReadTo(Char[], Char, Char, out Int32, StringReader.ReadOptions)

Advances the reader and reads until any character specified in keychars is encountered outside quotes. The reader's position after executing this method depends on the options.

Declaration
public string ReadTo(char[] keychars, char leftQuote, char rightQuote, out int hitIndex, StringReader.ReadOptions options = StringReader.ReadOptions.StopAfterKey | StringReader.ReadOptions.DiscardKey | StringReader.ReadOptions.ReadToEnd)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Char[] keychars

The reader stops when any of these characters is encountered.
System.Char leftQuote

The left quote. The reader will not stop when any of the keychars is encountered inside a pair of quotes.
System.Char rightQuote

The right quote. The reader will not stop when any of the keychars is encountered inside a pair of quotes.
System.Int32 hitIndex

Returns the index of the encountered keychar in the keychars.
StringReader.ReadOptions options

Specifies the reading options.
Returns
Type Description
System.String

If ReadeOptions.ReadToEnd is specified in options, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of any of the keychars within the search scope when such character is found outside quotes, or a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the end of the search scope if such character is not found outside quotes.

If ReadeOptions.ReadToEnd is not specified, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of any of the keychars within the search scope when such character is found outside quotes, or null if such character is not found outside quotes.

The position of this reader after executing this method depends on if ReadOptions.StopAfterKey is specified. If ReadOptions.StopAfterKey is specified, then the character satisfying the predicate is included in the returned substring if ReadOptions.DiscardKey is also selected.

NOTE that the white spaces at the beginning of the substring will be trimmed if ReadeOptions.TrimStart is specified, and the white spaces at the end of the substring will be trimmed if ReadeOptions.TrimEnd is specified. Also NOTE that System.String.Empty will be returned if the length of the substring after trim is 0.

Advances the reader and reads until a character specified by keychars is encountered outside quotes. The reader's position after executing this method depends on the options.

Declaration
public string ReadTo(char[] keychars, char[] primaryLeftQuotes, char[] primaryRightQuotes, char secondaryLeftQuote, char secondaryRightQuote, out int hitIndex, StringReader.ReadOptions options = StringReader.ReadOptions.StopAfterKey | StringReader.ReadOptions.DiscardKey | StringReader.ReadOptions.ReadToEnd)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Char[] keychars

The reader stops when any character in this array is encountered outside quotes. The reader will not stop when an element of the keychars is encountered inside a pair of primary/secondary quotes.
System.Char[] primaryLeftQuotes

Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the primary left quotes. A left quote of an index of this array corresponds to the right quote of that index of the array specified by primaryRightQuotes.
System.Char[] primaryRightQuotes

Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the primary right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by primaryLeftQuotes.
System.Char secondaryLeftQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the secondary left quote. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
System.Char secondaryRightQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the secondary right quote. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
System.Int32 hitIndex

Returns the index of the encountered keychar in the keychars.
StringReader.ReadOptions options

Specifies the reading options.
Returns
Type Description
System.String

If ReadeOptions.ReadToEnd is specified in options, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of any of the keychars within the search scope when such character is found outside quotes, or a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the end of the search scope if such character is not found outside quotes.

If ReadeOptions.ReadToEnd is not specified, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first occurrence of any of the keychars within the search scope when such character is found outside quotes, or null if such character is not found outside quotes.

The position of this reader after executing this method depends on if ReadOptions.StopAfterKey is specified. If ReadOptions.StopAfterKey is specified, then the character satisfying the predicate is included in the returned substring if ReadOptions.DiscardKey is also selected.

NOTE that the white spaces at the beginning of the substring will be trimmed if ReadeOptions.TrimStart is specified, and the white spaces at the end of the substring will be trimmed if ReadeOptions.TrimEnd is specified. Also NOTE that System.String.Empty will be returned if the length of the substring after trim is 0.

Advances the reader and reads until a character satisfying the specified predicate (called key char) is encountered outside quotes. The reader's position after executing this method depends on the options.

Declaration
public string ReadTo(Func<char, bool> predicate, char primaryLeftQuote, char primaryRightQuote, char secondaryLeftQuote, char secondaryRightQuote, StringReader.ReadOptions options = StringReader.ReadOptions.StopAfterKey | StringReader.ReadOptions.DiscardKey | StringReader.ReadOptions.ReadToEnd)
Parameters
Type Name Description

Specifies the Unicode character as the primary left quote.

Specifies the Unicode character as the primary right quote.

Specifies the reading options.
Returns
Type Description
System.String

If ReadeOptions.ReadToEnd is not specified, then a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found, or null if such character is not found.

The position of this reader after executing this method depends on if ReadOptions.StopAfterKey" is specified. If ReadOptions.StopAfterKey" is specified, then the character satisfying the predicate is included in the returned substring if ReadOptions.DiscardKey is also selected.

Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the primary right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by primaryLeftQuotes.
System.Char secondaryLeftQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the secondary left quote. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
System.Char secondaryRightQuote

Specifies the Unicode character as the secondary right quote. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
StringReader.ReadOptions options

Specifies the reading options.
Returns
Type Description
System.String

If ReadeOptions.ReadToEnd is specified in options, then a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found, or a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the end of the search scope if such character is not found.

If ReadeOptions.ReadToEnd is not specified, then a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found, or null if such character is not found.

The position of this reader after executing this method depends on if ReadOptions.StopAfterKey" is specified. If ReadOptions.StopAfterKey" is specified, then the character satisfying the predicate is included in the returned substring if ReadOptions.DiscardKey is also selected.

NOTE that the white spaces at the beginning of the substring will be trimmed if ReadeOptions.TrimStart is specified, and the white spaces at the end of the substring will be trimmed if ReadeOptions.TrimEnd is specified. Also NOTE that System.String.Empty will be returned if the length of the substring after trim is 0.
| Improve this Doc View Source

ReadToAsReader(Func<Char, Boolean>, Char, Char, StringReader.ReadOptions)

Advances the reader and reads until a character satisfying predicate (key char) is encountered outside quotes. The reader's position after executing this method depends on the options.

Declaration
public StringReader ReadToAsReader(Func<char, bool> predicate, char leftQuote, char rightQuote, StringReader.ReadOptions options = StringReader.ReadOptions.StopAfterKey | StringReader.ReadOptions.DiscardKey)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Func<System.Char, System.Boolean> predicate

A method to test each character of the reading scope and determines whether it is a key char.
System.Char leftQuote

The left quote. The reader will not stop when a key char is encountered inside a pair of quotes.
System.Char rightQuote

The right quote. The reader will not stop when a key char is encountered inside a pair of quotes.
StringReader.ReadOptions options

Specifies the reading options.
Returns
Type Description
StringReader

If ReadeOptions.ReadToEnd is specified in options, then a new reader will be returned encapsulating either a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope when such character is found, or a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the end of the search scope if such character is not found.

If ReadeOptions.ReadToEnd is not specified, then a new reader will be returned encapsulating a substring starting from the current position of the underlying string instance to the position of the first character satisfying the predicate within the search scope. When such character cannot be found, a null reference will be returned.

The position of this reader after executing this method depends on if ReadOptions.StopAfterKey is specified. If ReadOptions.StopAfterKey is specified, then the character satisfying the predicate is included in the returned new reader if ReadOptions.DiscardKey is also selected.

NOTE that the white spaces at the beginning of the substring will be trimmed if ReadeOptions.TrimStart is specified, and the white spaces at the end of the substring will be trimmed if ReadeOptions.TrimEnd is specified. Also NOTE that EmptyReader will be returned if the length of the substring after trim is 0.
| Improve this Doc View Source

ReadToEnd()

Advances this reader to the end of the search scope and returns a substring starting from the current position to the end of the search scope. NOTE that after executing this method, this reader is marked EOF and is no longer readable.

Declaration
public string ReadToEnd()
Returns
Type Description
System.String

A substring of the underlying string of this reader, starting from the current position to the end of the reading scope, if the current reader is not marked EOF; otherwise, System.String.Empty.

ReadToWhiteSpace(StringReader.ReadOptions)

Advances the reader and reads until the first whitespace is encountered. The CurrentPosition after executing this method depends on the options.

Declaration
public string ReadToWhiteSpace(StringReader.ReadOptions options = StringReader.ReadOptions.StopAfterKey | StringReader.ReadOptions.DiscardKey | StringReader.ReadOptions.ReadToEnd)
Parameters
Type Name Description
StringReader.ReadOptions options

Specifies the reading options.
Returns
Type Description
System.String

If ReadToEnd is specified in options, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first whitespace within the search scope, or a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the end of the scope if no whitespace is found; If ReadToEnd is not specified, then null is returned if no whitespace is found.

If StopAfterKey is specified, then the reader stops at the position after the first whitespace; otherwise the reader stops at the position of the encountered whitespace.

The whitespace is included in the returned substring if neither DiscardKey nor TrimEnd is specified.

The whitespaces at the beginning of the returned substring will be trimmed if TrimStart is specified; System.String.Empty will be returned if the length of the substring after trim is 0.
| Improve this Doc View Source

Type Description
System.String

If ReadToEnd is specified in options, then a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the position of the first whitespace or keyChr within the search scope, or a substring starting from the current position of the reading scope to the end of the scope if neither whitespace nor keyChr is found; If ReadToEnd is not specified, then null is returned if neither whitespace nor keyChr is found.

If StopAfterKey is specified, then the reader stops at the position after the first whitespace; otherwise the reader stops at the position of the encountered whitespace or keyChr.

The whitespace or keyChr is included in the returned substring if neither DiscardKey nor TrimEnd is specified.

The whitespaces at the beginning of the returned substring will be trimmed if TrimStart is specified; System.String.Empty will be returned if the length of the substring after trim is 0.
| Improve this Doc View Source

The reader will not stop when a character satisfying the predicate is encountered inside a pair of quotes.
System.Char[] rightQuotes

The left quotes that work together with leftQuotes to escape the predicate. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by leftQuotes. The reader will not stop when a character satisfying the predicate is encountered inside a pair of quotes.
System.Boolean skipKeyword

true if the reader stops at the position next to the last character of the encountered keyword. false if the reader stops at the position of the first character of the encountered keyword.
System.Boolean seekToEndIfKeywordNotFound

true if the reader should advance to the end of the reading scope if keyword is not found. false if the reader should stand still if such a keyword cannot be found.
Returns
Type Description
System.Boolean

true if an occurrence of keyword is encountered outside quotes and the reader is advanced to that keyword; false if no such keyword is found.
| Improve this Doc View Source

Gets a substring starting from the specified prevPos to the character previous to the CurrentPosition.

Note this method returns null if prevPos equals CurrentPosition.

Declaration
public string SubstringBeforeCurrentPosition(int prevPos)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.Int32 prevPos

Provides a position prior to the reader's CurrentPosition.
Returns
Type Description
System.String

A substring starting from the specified prevPos to the character previous to the CurrentPosition. Note the first character of the current reading scope is not contained in the returned substring. null is returned if prevPos equals CurrentPosition.
